---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="An LLM Predicts the Next Token">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L01" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What does an LLM actually predict?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        An LLM does exactly one thing: given a sequence of tokens, it predicts which token comes next.
      </p>
      <p>
        It does not "understand" language. It does not "think." It computes a score for every token in its vocabulary, and the highest-scoring token is the prediction.
      </p>
      <p>
        Generation — the process of producing long outputs — is just this one-step prediction repeated.
        The model predicts one token, that token is appended to the sequence, and the model predicts again.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is called <strong>autoregressive generation</strong>. The model's output becomes its own input on the next step.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">One-step prediction:</p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-secondary); min-width: 60px;">input:</span>
            <span style="color: var(--sem-token);">["The", " cat", " sat"]</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-secondary); min-width: 60px;">output:</span>
            <span style="color: var(--sem-logits);">" on"</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">(highest-scoring next token)</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top: var(--border-subtle); margin-top: var(--space-4); padding-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Autoregressive generation repeats this:</p>
          <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--ink-secondary); display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px;">
            <div>Step 1: ["The", " cat", " sat"] → <span style="color: var(--sem-logits);">" on"</span></div>
            <div>Step 2: ["The", " cat", " sat", " on"] → <span style="color: var(--sem-logits);">" the"</span></div>
            <div>Step 3: ["The", " cat", " sat", " on", " the"] → <span style="color: var(--sem-logits);">" mat"</span></div>
            <div>Step 4: ["The", " cat", " sat", " on", " the", " mat"] → <span style="color: var(--sem-logits);">"."</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <p>We are not working with tensor shapes yet. The key idea here is sequence growth:</p>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>step 1 input length: 3 tokens</div>
        <div>step 2 input length: 4 tokens</div>
        <div>step 3 input length: 5 tokens</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">The sequence grows by one token at each step.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <p>No math is required yet. The only concept is:</p>
      <ul style="list-style: disc; padding-left: var(--space-5); font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
        <li>The model takes a sequence of token IDs and produces scores for every possible next token.</li>
        <li>The prediction step does not depend on future tokens — only on what came before.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          In <code>llama.cpp</code>, the autoregressive loop lives in the server and CLI tools.
          The model graph itself is evaluated once per step. You will see this in the case studies later.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Because generation is iterative, the time to produce N tokens is roughly N times the time for one step.
          Making each step fast is the central performance goal. Later, you will learn why the first step (prefill) and subsequent steps (decode) behave very differently.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L01"
        gateStrength="soft"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L01-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'In one sentence, what does the model predict?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'The meaning of the input sentence', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'The next token in the sequence', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'All remaining tokens at once', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The model predicts one next token per step. Multi-token output comes from repeating this process.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L01-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Why is generation called "autoregressive"?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Because it uses regression analysis', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Because each prediction depends on the model\'s own previous outputs', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Because it runs automatically without human input', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The model\'s own output at step N becomes part of its input at step N+1. This self-feeding loop is what "autoregressive" means.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
